data: {"type":"layer1","modelId":"local/apple-fm","model":"Crucible (offline)","text":"## Zod Schema for IPv4 Address Validation\n\n```typescript\nimport { Schema } from 'zod';\n\nconst ipv4Schema: Schema<string> = {\n  type: 'string',\n  pattern: /^(?:[0-9]{1,3}\\.){3}[0-9]{1,3}$/,\n};\n\nexport default ipv4Schema;\n```\n\n## Explanation\n\n- **Type:** `string`: This specifies that the input must be a string.\n- **Pattern:** `^(?:[0-9]{1,3}\\.){3}[0-9]{1,3}$/: This is a regular expression that matches a valid IPv4 address.\n  - `^`: Asserts the start of the string.\n  - `(?:[0-9]{1,3})`: Matches one or more digits from 0 to 9, representing a segment of the IPv4 address.\n  - `\\.)`: Matches a dot (.) to separate the segments.\n  - `{3}`: Ensures there are exactly three dots.\n  - `[0-9]{1,3}$`: Matches one or more digits from 0 to 9, representing the last segment of the IPv4 address.\n\nThis schema ensures that the input string adheres to the standard format of an IPv4 address, with four decimal numbers separated by dots.","done":true}

data: {"type":"stage","stage":1,"status":"done"}

data: {"type":"synthesis","modelId":"local/apple-fm","model":"Crucible","text":"## Zod Schema for IPv4 Address Validation\n\n```typescript\nimport { Schema } from 'zod';\n\nconst ipv4Schema: Schema<string> = {\n  type: 'string',\n  pattern: /^(?:[0-9]{1,3}\\.){3}[0-9]{1,3}$/,\n};\n\nexport default ipv4Schema;\n```\n\n## Explanation\n\n- **Type:** `string`: This specifies that the input must be a string.\n- **Pattern:** `^(?:[0-9]{1,3}\\.){3}[0-9]{1,3}$/: This is a regular expression that matches a valid IPv4 address.\n  - `^`: Asserts the start of the string.\n  - `(?:[0-9]{1,3})`: Matches one or more digits from 0 to 9, representing a segment of the IPv4 address.\n  - `\\.)`: Matches a dot (.) to separate the segments.\n  - `{3}`: Ensures there are exactly three dots.\n  - `[0-9]{1,3}$`: Matches one or more digits from 0 to 9, representing the last segment of the IPv4 address.\n\nThis schema ensures that the input string adheres to the standard format of an IPv4 address, with four decimal numbers separated by dots.","done":true,"replace":true}

